'''Sudbury''' is a village and [[civil parish]] in [[Derbyshire]], [[England]], located approximately 11 miles to the south of [[Ashbourne, Derbyshire|Ashbourne]]. It is part of the [[Derbyshire Dales]] district. The £0.5m [[A50 road|A50]] bypass opened in 1972.

[[Sudbury Hall]] and [[Sudbury (HM Prison)|HM Prison Sudbury]] are located here.

'''[[Population]]''' - 643 (1991 Census)

==History==
Sudbury was mentioned in the [[Domesday book]] as belonging to [[Henry de Ferrers]] and was worth twenty shillings<ref name = "Domesday">''Domesday Book: A Complete Translation''. London: Penguin, 2003. ISBN 0-14-143994-7 p.746</ref>.

==Famous Residents==
* [[Edward Venables-Vernon-Harcourt|Edward Harcourt]], [[Archbishop of York]], was born here
* [[William Vernon Harcourt (scientist)|William Harcourt]] founder of the [[British Association for the Advancement of Science]] was born here in 1789<ref>[[Encyclopædia Britannica Eleventh Edition]]</ref>.
* [[George John Venables-Vernon, 5th Baron Vernon|George John Warren Vernon]], M.P. and [[Dante]] enthusiast was born here in 1803

